{
  "text": "We remark that one can also approximate the kernel (22) and the Atkinson-Cabrera solution [CITATION_1] by replacing the infinite sums with the finite ones that include the first N r roots of (11) near the origin. Using this approximation instead of the numerical evaluation of the integral, we obtained results that suggest convergence of the displacement and stress values as N r is increased. For example, at N r = 400, the kinetic relation is very close to the one shown in Fig. 5 , the difference being of the order ranging from 10 \u22125 for the smaller velocities to 10 \u22127 . On the other hand, the shape functions h(\u03be) obtained using the truncated kernel method feature additional fine-scale oscillations due to a Gibbs-type phenomenon associated with the delta-function singularities at the end points. These oscillations are probably an artifact of the truncation. ",
  "correct_citation": {
    "[CITATION_1]": "36774415"
